1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,160
Right now, you are thinking a thought.

2
00:00:03,160 --> 00:00:04,920
So try something with me.

3
00:00:04,920 --> 00:00:06,680
Guess your next thought.

4
00:00:06,680 --> 00:00:07,880
Not think it.

5
00:00:07,880 --> 00:00:08,840
Guess it.

6
00:00:08,840 --> 00:00:10,520
Before it arrives.

7
00:00:10,520 --> 00:00:11,800
Go.

8
00:00:11,800 --> 00:00:13,560
You cannot, can you?

9
00:00:13,560 --> 00:00:15,120
It just shows up.

10
00:00:15,120 --> 00:00:17,320
On its own, fully formed,

11
00:00:17,320 --> 00:00:19,840
like it wandered in from another room.

12
00:00:19,840 --> 00:00:21,280
Stan tries it.

13
00:00:21,280 --> 00:00:22,560
And out of nowhere,

14
00:00:22,560 --> 00:00:26,320
his brain serves up a random craving for a sandwich.

15
00:00:26,320 --> 00:00:27,960
Where did that come from?

16
00:00:27,960 --> 00:00:29,840
He did not decide to think it.

17
00:00:29,840 --> 00:00:31,360
It just appeared.

18
00:00:31,360 --> 00:00:34,000
You feel like the author of your thoughts.

19
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:35,640
But the truth is a lot stranger.

20
00:00:35,640 --> 00:00:37,440
And once you see it,

21
00:00:37,440 --> 00:00:40,680
the voice in your head will never sound quite the same.

22
00:00:40,680 --> 00:00:44,200
We go through life assuming we are the one doing the thinking.

23
00:00:44,200 --> 00:00:45,360
I think,

24
00:00:45,360 --> 00:00:47,280
therefore I am, right?

25
00:00:47,280 --> 00:00:48,680
I am the boss up here,

26
00:00:48,680 --> 00:00:51,560
writing each thought one after another.

27
00:00:51,560 --> 00:00:53,800
But watch your own mind for 10 seconds

28
00:00:53,800 --> 00:00:56,600
and that whole idea starts to fall apart.

29
00:00:56,600 --> 00:00:58,880
A song you have not heard in years,

30
00:00:58,880 --> 00:01:02,000
a worry, a cringe memory from 2009.

31
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:04,240
None of it was invited, it arrived.

32
00:01:04,240 --> 00:01:07,120
And here's where it gets genuinely weird.

33
00:01:07,120 --> 00:01:09,520
If you are really in charge, then prove it.

34
00:01:09,520 --> 00:01:10,840
Try the opposite.

35
00:01:10,840 --> 00:01:12,360
For the next few seconds,

36
00:01:12,360 --> 00:01:14,480
do not think about a white bear.

37
00:01:14,480 --> 00:01:17,600
Whatever you do, no white bears.

38
00:01:17,600 --> 00:01:19,000
And there it is.

39
00:01:19,000 --> 00:01:20,960
You cannot not think about it.

40
00:01:20,960 --> 00:01:22,520
Almost 200 years ago,

41
00:01:22,520 --> 00:01:24,840
the writer Dostoevsky dared his brother

42
00:01:24,840 --> 00:01:26,400
with exactly this.

43
00:01:26,400 --> 00:01:29,480
And psychologists later confirmed it in the lab.

44
00:01:29,480 --> 00:01:31,800
The harder you try to push a thought away,

45
00:01:31,800 --> 00:01:33,360
the harder it shoves back.

46
00:01:33,360 --> 00:01:36,040
So sit with the full picture.

47
00:01:36,040 --> 00:01:38,480
You cannot summon your next thought.

48
00:01:38,480 --> 00:01:40,200
And you cannot banish one either.

49
00:01:40,200 --> 00:01:42,320
If you were truly running the show in there,

50
00:01:42,320 --> 00:01:44,040
both of those should be easy.

51
00:01:44,040 --> 00:01:45,880
Neither one is.

52
00:01:45,880 --> 00:01:48,920
There is a reason for that hiding in plain sight.

53
00:01:48,920 --> 00:01:52,520
You literally cannot think a thought before you think it.

54
00:01:52,520 --> 00:01:53,880
To plan it in advance,

55
00:01:53,880 --> 00:01:55,920
you would already have to be thinking it.

56
00:01:55,920 --> 00:01:57,720
Which means every thought you have arrives

57
00:01:57,720 --> 00:01:59,840
from somewhere you cannot see

58
00:01:59,840 --> 00:02:02,000
a moment before you notice it.

59
00:02:02,000 --> 00:02:05,360
You are not sitting at the keyboard, typing your thoughts.

60
00:02:05,360 --> 00:02:08,360
You are reading them off the screen as they appear.

61
00:02:08,360 --> 00:02:10,800
And your brain is doing this constantly,

62
00:02:10,800 --> 00:02:13,160
even when you feel like you are doing nothing.

63
00:02:13,160 --> 00:02:15,000
There is a whole network in there

64
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:16,920
called the default mode network

65
00:02:16,920 --> 00:02:20,160
that switches on the second you stop concentrating

66
00:02:20,160 --> 00:02:22,960
and it just generates daydreams,

67
00:02:23,040 --> 00:02:26,320
replays, random what ifs.

68
00:02:26,320 --> 00:02:30,000
It is why your best ideas tend to ambush you in the shower

69
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:33,320
or on a walk the moment you stop trying.

70
00:02:33,320 --> 00:02:35,840
This thing takes over and starts handing you things

71
00:02:35,840 --> 00:02:37,760
you were not even looking for.

72
00:02:37,760 --> 00:02:40,280
And it runs more than you would ever guess.

73
00:02:40,280 --> 00:02:43,200
Harvard researchers ping thousands of people at random

74
00:02:43,200 --> 00:02:46,160
through their days to ask where their mind was.

75
00:02:46,160 --> 00:02:50,200
The answer, wandering about 47% of the time.

76
00:02:50,200 --> 00:02:52,080
Nearly half your waking life,

77
00:02:52,080 --> 00:02:54,240
you are not really where your body is.

78
00:02:54,240 --> 00:02:55,720
You are off somewhere,

79
00:02:55,720 --> 00:02:58,320
carried around by thoughts you never chose.

80
00:02:58,320 --> 00:03:00,520
And it might go deeper than thoughts.

81
00:03:00,520 --> 00:03:03,440
It might reach all the way down into your choices.

82
00:03:03,440 --> 00:03:06,200
In the 1980s, a scientist named Benjamin Libet

83
00:03:06,200 --> 00:03:08,040
wired people up to a brain scanner

84
00:03:08,040 --> 00:03:10,400
and gave them one simple job.

85
00:03:10,400 --> 00:03:11,960
Watch a fast clock.

86
00:03:11,960 --> 00:03:14,680
And whenever you feel like it, flick your wrist.

87
00:03:14,680 --> 00:03:17,560
Just note the exact moment you decided to move.

88
00:03:17,560 --> 00:03:20,040
And the results were genuinely unsettling.

89
00:03:20,040 --> 00:03:21,720
The brain started gearing up to move

90
00:03:21,720 --> 00:03:24,560
a full third of a second, sometimes more,

91
00:03:24,560 --> 00:03:27,040
before the person felt they had decided.

92
00:03:27,040 --> 00:03:29,640
The decision showed up in the brain first.

93
00:03:29,640 --> 00:03:32,720
The feeling of, I chose this came second.

94
00:03:32,720 --> 00:03:34,520
As if you are not making the call,

95
00:03:34,520 --> 00:03:36,880
you are being told about it a beat late.

96
00:03:36,880 --> 00:03:38,960
Now, be careful with this one.

97
00:03:38,960 --> 00:03:40,480
It is fiercely debated.

98
00:03:40,480 --> 00:03:43,000
It only covers tiny, simple movements.

99
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:46,080
And Libet himself did not think it killed free will.

100
00:03:46,080 --> 00:03:49,160
He pointed out that even after the impulse builds,

101
00:03:49,160 --> 00:03:53,280
the conscious mind can still veto it at the last instant.

102
00:03:53,280 --> 00:03:57,000
Call it free won't, but strip it all down

103
00:03:57,000 --> 00:03:59,840
and you are left with the same strange shape.

104
00:03:59,840 --> 00:04:01,800
The impulse arrives on its own.

105
00:04:01,800 --> 00:04:05,400
What you do with it is the only part that might be yours.

106
00:04:05,400 --> 00:04:08,440
And if your head is spinning, take some comfort

107
00:04:08,440 --> 00:04:10,320
because humans did not even know

108
00:04:10,320 --> 00:04:13,600
where thoughts came from for almost all of history.

109
00:04:13,600 --> 00:04:15,840
The ancient Egyptians were so certain

110
00:04:15,840 --> 00:04:18,920
the brain did not matter that during mummification,

111
00:04:18,960 --> 00:04:21,000
they slid a hook up through the nose,

112
00:04:21,000 --> 00:04:24,880
scooped the brain out and threw it in the trash.

113
00:04:24,880 --> 00:04:26,120
But the heart?

114
00:04:26,120 --> 00:04:28,520
The heart they preserved with enormous care

115
00:04:28,520 --> 00:04:31,600
and weighed in the afterlife against a feather.

116
00:04:31,600 --> 00:04:34,440
Because they believed the heart was where you did your thinking

117
00:04:34,440 --> 00:04:36,120
and feeling.

118
00:04:36,120 --> 00:04:38,120
And it was not just them.

119
00:04:38,120 --> 00:04:41,440
Aristotle, one of the sharpest minds who ever lived,

120
00:04:41,440 --> 00:04:44,080
decided the brain was basically a radiator,

121
00:04:44,080 --> 00:04:47,400
a wet sponge whose only job was to cool the blood.

122
00:04:47,440 --> 00:04:50,960
And that real thought happened in the heart.

123
00:04:50,960 --> 00:04:53,600
And here's the part that should give you chills.

124
00:04:53,600 --> 00:04:56,280
That ancient mistake is still hiding inside

125
00:04:56,280 --> 00:04:58,080
the way you talk right now.

126
00:04:58,080 --> 00:05:01,360
When you memorize something, you learn it by heart.

127
00:05:01,360 --> 00:05:04,880
When you mean something truly, it is heartfelt.

128
00:05:04,880 --> 00:05:06,440
You know it by heart.

129
00:05:06,440 --> 00:05:09,320
Every one of those phrases is a little fossil.

130
00:05:09,320 --> 00:05:11,800
Left over from thousands of years of humans

131
00:05:11,800 --> 00:05:14,960
being dead certain that the heart did the thinking.

132
00:05:14,960 --> 00:05:18,000
The actual organ generating every word of this sentence

133
00:05:18,000 --> 00:05:21,800
in your head did not even get the credit in our language.

134
00:05:21,800 --> 00:05:25,400
So here's the quiet, strange truth under all of it.

135
00:05:25,400 --> 00:05:28,400
The thing you call me, that voice narrating your life

136
00:05:28,400 --> 00:05:31,840
this very second is not the source of your thoughts.

137
00:05:31,840 --> 00:05:33,920
It is the one they happen to.

138
00:05:33,920 --> 00:05:38,000
Everything you have ever seen, heard, feared, and loved

139
00:05:38,000 --> 00:05:40,480
is churning away beneath your awareness,

140
00:05:40,480 --> 00:05:42,280
recombining in the dark.

141
00:05:42,280 --> 00:05:44,320
And every so often, it hands a finished thought

142
00:05:44,360 --> 00:05:45,640
up to the surface.

143
00:05:45,640 --> 00:05:49,240
And you, the part that notices, take the credit.

144
00:05:49,240 --> 00:05:51,160
You are not the writer in the room.

145
00:05:51,160 --> 00:05:53,960
You are the reader, turning pages you did not write.

146
00:05:53,960 --> 00:05:57,600
And somehow, that reader is the most you there is.

147
00:05:57,600 --> 00:06:00,800
Which is actually freeing once it lands.

148
00:06:00,800 --> 00:06:03,440
That cruel little thought that ambushes you,

149
00:06:03,440 --> 00:06:07,000
that worry at 2am, that random ugly thing

150
00:06:07,000 --> 00:06:09,680
your brain blurts for no reason at all.

151
00:06:09,680 --> 00:06:12,520
You did not write it, it arrived on its own.

152
00:06:12,520 --> 00:06:14,800
From a process you do not control.

153
00:06:14,800 --> 00:06:17,320
The same way, the white bear did.

154
00:06:17,320 --> 00:06:19,320
So you do not have to believe it,

155
00:06:19,320 --> 00:06:20,880
and you do not have to be ashamed of it.

156
00:06:20,880 --> 00:06:23,720
Because it was never really yours to begin with.

157
00:06:23,720 --> 00:06:25,960
The thoughts show up by themselves.

158
00:06:25,960 --> 00:06:28,640
The one part that is truly yours

159
00:06:28,640 --> 00:06:31,320
is what you choose to do with the ones that come.

160
00:06:31,320 --> 00:06:34,600
So the next time a thought appears out of nowhere,

161
00:06:34,600 --> 00:06:36,520
see it for what it really is.

162
00:06:36,520 --> 00:06:38,960
A message handed up from a place inside you

163
00:06:38,960 --> 00:06:40,760
that you will never fully see,

164
00:06:40,760 --> 00:06:43,400
delivered to the one part of you that gets to read it,

165
00:06:43,400 --> 00:06:44,800
and decide.

166
00:06:44,800 --> 00:06:46,560
You have spent your whole life certain

167
00:06:46,560 --> 00:06:48,800
that you are the one doing the thinking.

168
00:06:48,800 --> 00:06:52,160
It turns out you are the one lucky enough to be listening.

